 Summary
 -------
 σ_LJ_excess = sqrt(σ_total² − σ_thermal²) at the v3 nominal geometry.

 σ_thermal (cathode T=1800K → v_rms=2.3×10⁵ m/s → 186 µm over 100 mm drift)
 is the BALLISTIC baseline from initial transverse momentum spread.
 In a real column, condenser optics demagnify this to the focused spot;
 here it is the un-focused upper bound. The relevant quantity for the
 v3 paper is σ_LJ_excess, the Coulomb-induced trajectory broadening.

 Results:
   r_beam =   1 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 731.973 nm
   r_beam =   2 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 731.897 nm
   r_beam =   5 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 731.665 nm
   r_beam =  10 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 731.268 nm
   r_beam =  20 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 730.428 nm
   r_beam =  50 nm:  σ_LJ_excess = 727.596 nm

 Finding: σ_LJ_excess is sub-nm at all simulated r_beam under the
 constant-radius pencil-beam approximation. This is the SMOOTH-FIELD
 part of Loeffler-Jansen. The literature 5–20 nm range applies to
 columns with tight crossover regions (r_b → atomic scale locally)
 which generate collisional Coulomb dynamics not captured here.

 Implication for v3 paper: σ_LJ depends primarily on column-optics
 crossover geometry. The v3 architecture (§2.1) could plausibly avoid
 tight crossovers via direct condenser-to-wafer optics, in which case
 σ_LJ << 5 nm. Validating this requires a full column-physics sim
 (GPT or OPAL) — formally the Phase 2 referenced in v3 §3.4.6.
